<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Vertex Degree</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"267.469" src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/VertexDegrees_1000.svg" class=3D"=
" alt=3D"VertexDegrees">
</div>
<p>
The degree of a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GraphVertex.html">=
graph vertex</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations=
/VertexDegree/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%=
;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"8" height=3D"21" alt=3D"v"> of a <a =
href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Graph.html">graph</a> <img src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/VertexDegree/Inline2.svg" class=
=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" wi=
dth=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D"G">, also called the vertex degree or local=
 degree, is the number
 of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GraphEdge.html">graph edges</a=
> which touch <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Ve=
rtexDegree/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;ma=
x-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"8" height=3D"21" alt=3D"v">. The vertex=
 degrees are illustrated above for a random graph.
 The vertex degree is also called the local degree or valency. The ordered =
list of
 vertex degrees in a given graph is called its <a href=3D"https://mathworld=
.wolfram.com/DegreeSequence.html">degree
 sequence</a>. A list of vertex degrees of a graph can be computed in the <=
a href=3D"http://www.wolfram.com/language/">Wolfram
 Language</a> using <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/re=
f/VertexDegree.html">VertexDegree</a></tt>[<i>g</i>],
 and precomputed vertex degrees are available for particular embeddings of =
many named
 graphs via <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/GraphD=
ata.html">GraphData</a></tt>[<i>graph</i>,
 <tt>"VertexDegrees"</tt>].
</p>
<p>
The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/MinimumVertexDegree.html">mini=
mum vertex degree</a> in a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Graph.h=
tml">graph</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/V=
ertexDegree/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;m=
ax-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" alt=3D"G"> is denote=
d <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/VertexDegree/I=
nline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%=
" border=3D"0" width=3D"35" height=3D"21" alt=3D"delta(G)">, and the <a hre=
f=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/MaximumVertexDegree.html">maximum
 vertex degree</a> is denoted <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/VertexDegree/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"ma=
x-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"38" height=3D"21" alt=
=3D"Delta(G)"> (Skiena 1990, p.&nbsp;157).
</p>
<p>
The <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GraphVertex.html">graph vertex=
</a> degree of a point <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equ=
ations/VertexDegree/Inline7.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-heigh=
t:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"8" height=3D"21" alt=3D"v"> in=
 a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Graph.html">graph</a>, denoted =
<img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/VertexDegree/Inl=
ine8.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" =
border=3D"0" width=3D"32" height=3D"21" alt=3D"rho(v)">, satisfies
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/VertexDegree/NumberedEquation1.svg" class=3D"numberedequation=
" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"104" heigh=
t=3D"50" alt=3D" sum_(i=3D1)^nrho(v_i)=3D2E, "></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
where <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/VertexDegr=
ee/Inline9.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:=
100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"12" height=3D"21" alt=3D"E">
 is the total number of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GraphEdge.=
html">graph edges</a>.
</p>
<p>
In addition, a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ConnectedGraph.html=
">connected graph</a> nodes satisfies
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/VertexDegree/NumberedEquation2.svg" class=3D"numberedequation=
" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"137" heigh=
t=3D"50" alt=3D" sum_(i=3D1)^nrho(v_i)&gt;=3D1/2(n-1), "></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
where the inequality can be made strict except in the case of the <a href=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SingletonGraph.html">singleton graph</a> =
<img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/VertexDegree/Inl=
ine10.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%"=
 border=3D"0" width=3D"20" height=3D"21" alt=3D"K_1">.
 However, while this condition is <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/=
Necessary.html">necessary</a> for a graph
 to be <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ConnectedGraph.html">connec=
ted</a>, it is not <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Sufficient.html=
">sufficient</a>;
 an arbitrary graph satisfying the above inequality may be <a href=3D"https=
://mathworld.wolfram.com/ConnectedGraph.html">connected</a>
 or <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/DisconnectedGraph.html">discon=
nected</a>. In fact, the criterion is
 not useful for connectedness testing since almost all disconnected graphs =
(with the
 exception of some disjoint unions of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
